Exercise 9: Implementing the Command Pattern

## Aim

To implement the Command Design Pattern for a home automation system that can turn devices on and off using commands.

## Project Name

CommandPatternExample

## Project Structure

```text id="w8f2mk"
CommandPatternExample
│
├── Command.java
├── Light.java
├── LightOnCommand.java
├── LightOffCommand.java
├── RemoteControl.java
└── CommandTest.java
```

## 1. Define Command Interface

### Command.java

```java id="n3x7qb"
public interface Command {
    void execute();
}
```

## 2. Implement Receiver Class

### Light.java

```java id="0w9vce"
public class Light {

    public void turnOn() {
        System.out.println("Light is ON");
    }

    public void turnOff() {
        System.out.println("Light is OFF");
    }
}
```

## 3. Implement Concrete Commands

### LightOnCommand.java

```java id="j6r2ha"
public class LightOnCommand implements Command {

    private Light light;

    public LightOnCommand(Light light) {
        this.light = light;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        light.turnOn();
    }
}
```

### LightOffCommand.java

```java id="p5m8dk"
public class LightOffCommand implements Command {

    private Light light;

    public LightOffCommand(Light light) {
        this.light = light;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        light.turnOff();
    }
}
```

## 4. Implement Invoker Class

### RemoteControl.java

```java id="u1t9yl"
public class RemoteControl {

    private Command command;

    public void setCommand(Command command) {
        this.command = command;
    }

    public void pressButton() {
        command.execute();
    }
}
```

## 5. Test the Command Pattern

### CommandTest.java

```java id="y7e4qb"
public class CommandTest {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Light light = new Light();

        Command lightOn = new LightOnCommand(light);
        Command lightOff = new LightOffCommand(light);

        RemoteControl remote = new RemoteControl();

        remote.setCommand(lightOn);
        remote.pressButton();

        remote.setCommand(lightOff);
        remote.pressButton();
    }
}
```

## Output

```text id="0f4xgj"
Light is ON
Light is OFF
```

## Working

1. The `Command` interface declares the `execute()` method.
2. `Light` acts as the receiver and contains the actual business logic.
3. `LightOnCommand` and `LightOffCommand` are concrete command classes that invoke operations on the receiver.
4. `RemoteControl` acts as the invoker and triggers command execution.
5. The client creates command objects and assigns them to the remote control.
6. The remote control executes the assigned command without knowing the implementation details.

## Advantages of Command Pattern

1. Decouples the sender from the receiver.
2. Supports flexible command execution.
3. Makes it easy to add new commands.
4. Promotes code reusability and maintainability.
5. Supports features such as command queues, logging, and undo operations.

## Conclusion

The Command Pattern was successfully implemented using command objects to encapsulate requests for turning a light on and off. The RemoteControl invoker executes commands without directly interacting with the receiver. This design improves flexibility, scalability, and maintainability in home automation systems.
